{"key":"processedPost-10579821","value":{"id":10579821,"first":10578605,"last":10580648,"when":1246082081,"utime":"06/27/09 08:54 AM","cleanedPost":"They don't eat much and rarely lay eggs in the substrate, and if it's fully colonized, the larvae can't do much anyway and usually die.&nbsp; They're mostly just looking for a meal.&nbsp; Don't spray poison on them.&nbsp; Sticky traps are probably the best control if there's a lot.&nbsp; For only three or four, just ignore them.&nbsp; Some gnats go for wine or beer, but others don't.<br />Two common places they come from are houseplants that have been outdoors and brought back in, and the bathtub drain.&nbsp; Check both.&nbsp; If they're in the bathtub drain, a bit of drano will nuke them.&nbsp; Pour it in and then put a rag over the drain to hold the fumes and prevent them from escaping.<br />RR"}}